reviewText: This is the First show by writer Aaron Sorkin. the dialogue is snappy and fun showing all the promise that would eventually give us the West Wing. the characters are strong for a sitcom and most episodes are interesting (Despite my complete lack of interest in Sports of any kind).my only real complaint is that the show is a sitcom. the tone of the show is often serious and feels rushed, do to the 22 minute run time of a sitcom. also the Laugh track feels really out of place, you will sometime go half the show without anything funny happening and then suddenly someone tells a joke and the laugh track feel jarring and out of place.As it is the show is good. especially if you are a fan of Sorkins writing. but if it was an hour long dramady (like the West Wing or Studio 60) than it would have been great.
summary: Good but it could have Been Great.

reviewText: I have enjoyed everything that Mr. Sorkin has ever done and Sports Night was certainly no exception.  Both his drama and comedy are of the highest quality and the talent of Josh Charles, Joshua Malina, Peter Krause, Robert Guillaume (sp?), Sabrina Lloyd and Felicity Huffman certainly didn't hurt. To my way of thinking Mr. Sorkin knows how to take the ordinary to dramatic levels without overworking it or becoming maudlin.  So if you want some good drama and a few good laughs, I would suggest Sports Night.
summary: It's Aaron Sorkin -- need anything else be said.

reviewText: I love everything Sorkin.  But really, he's got to stop the token black man thing.  Can a sister get more than a background beat?  If you notice in Sports Night, Network (HBO), West Wing (Dule Hill) and Studio 60, Sorkin leans backward when it comes to sustained black relationships.  In Network he's building an ethnic-brown-whiteish relationship which I guess represents diversity but really?  This choice of safe othering is so Ivy League.  "Of course we are diverse--look how many Asians we have here. And my 'body man' is a straight shooting black man who's only motivation is the safety of the lead character.  In the West Wing it was Bartlett.I hate to be so critical.  I mean I have nothing but love for Sorkin.  He's one of the best writers in film and television.  I'm just saying that there are many bridges to cross--which is a good thing.
summary: Token-Token Burning Bright When will Sorkin realize this ain't right?

reviewText: When this show first aired, I couldn't get enough of it. Witty, fast-paced dialog in an energetic and fascinating setting. But it's cancellation freed Aaron Sorkin to create The West Wing — easily one of the best shows of all time.
